<b>Are you in conrol of EverQuest or is EverQuest in Control of You?</b><br><font size=1>Posted on  Sunday, December 31 @ 14:37:44 CST

</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td bgcolor=ffffff>
<a href=search.php?query=&topic=35&author=><img src=images/topics/gaming.jpg border=0 Alt="Games Games Games" align=right hspace=10 vspace=10></a>
This article, from <a href="http://www.gamers.com" target=_blank>gamers.com</a>, is actually about a "fake" real life suicide from a player a while back that "really" affected players in real life. Probably any EQ players already knows about this; it's old news. The article however had other good references to the additictive attributes of the game. More so is that it's about the player and not the game itself. I bring it up for the sake of discussion.
<p>
Click read more for an excerpt and links.
<br><br><br><br>"Many people come to EQ to get away from the stress and rigors of the real world. As you progress through the game, you make friends ,you talk to them and hang out with them in the game and everything is groovy. You get to know each other a bit beyond the characters, but as soon as someone has a bad day and needs to talk about it, it stops. They don't want to hear your dirty laundry. "<br><br>
This is when the online life takes its toll. "By this time, the player has spent so much time in game and so little time with real-life friends and family, that they are bitter and don't much want to talk," he said. "It is at this point where the EQ addict becomes very unstable and begins the downward spiral to depression."
<br><br>
Secias has been there. He and his girlfriend were playing EQ 16 hours a day. They would sometimes call each other by their character names away from the game. Their friends played drunk, got into fights with roommates over game events, and watched marriages break up over the game.
<br><br>
Pouring all that time into a game can have consequences that spill over into real life. "Before my eyes Isaw the relationship with my dream girl fade away. We never spoke, and when we did it was about EQ. We fought constantly. One day reality hit us square in the face and we thought to ourselves... ' We really need help. We need to fix this.' It was lucky for us that we were there for each other and could lean on each other for support, a luxury that most people do not have." They quit cold turkey.
<br><br>
He is quick to point out that Verant is not to blame for creating such a captivating game. Any online roleplaying game is appealing because it lacks the ugly stresses of reality. An avatar never ages, never gets sick or really dies. Slipping into another life is as easy as typing a new character name. The choice, however, to let the online world become more real than the off-line, is always in the hands of the player.
<br><BR>
--------------End Excerpt
<br><br>
The full article:<BR><BR>
